WEBVTT

00:02.120 --> 00:05.203
When I've achieved what
I've set out to achieve,

00:05.280 --> 00:07.089
I will let you know
where to find the guns.

00:07.600 --> 00:09.045
So what shall I do?

00:09.120 --> 00:11.851
Get close to him.
Find out where those guns are heading.

00:14.040 --> 00:15.963
Raise your hand,
all those who want to strike!

00:16.040 --> 00:17.565
(ALL CHEERING)

00:17.640 --> 00:20.484
Freddie Thorne is at the
very top of my list.

00:20.560 --> 00:23.803
Well, cross him off.
I'll make him part of our deal.

00:23.920 --> 00:27.322
To hell with them. The more they try
and stop us, the madder I'll be.

00:27.760 --> 00:30.411
In times like these, a communist
in family is bad for business.

00:30.800 --> 00:32.040
You have to leave the city.

00:34.800 --> 00:37.531
TOMMY: <i>You were also at war with
the Lees, Mr Kimber, am I right?</i>

00:38.080 --> 00:41.084
Together, we can beat them.
Divided, maybe not.

01:00.440 --> 01:01.601
(GIGGLING)

01:02.520 --> 01:04.090
God, he's getting big now!

01:04.840 --> 01:06.444
(IN DISTINCT CHATTER)

01:08.000 --> 01:09.161
Not at all.

01:12.360 --> 01:16.604
<i># Where the viaduct looms
like a bird of doom</i>

01:16.680 --> 01:19.729
<i># As it shifts and cracks</i>

01:20.760 --> 01:24.845
<i># Where secrets lie in the border fires</i>

01:24.920 --> 01:27.082
<i># In the humming wires... #</i>

01:27.160 --> 01:31.006
- So, how was London?
- It was crackling with revolution.

01:31.080 --> 01:33.481
The Poplar Docks are on strike.

01:33.560 --> 01:35.642
Did our friends give us
what we asked for?

01:38.680 --> 01:41.286
- How much?
-200 pounds.

01:41.680 --> 01:45.162
- Who did you meet?
- An attache from the Russian Embassy.

01:45.480 --> 01:47.642
In a Chinese restaurant.
(CHUCKLES)

01:48.680 --> 01:52.162
Our revolution is international.
It grows by the day.

02:08.280 --> 02:10.681
Jeremiah, Jeremiah, what do you see?

02:11.440 --> 02:13.522
Your sister and Freddie
got back this morning.

02:13.720 --> 02:17.964
I tried following them.
But Freddie's so good at getting away.

02:18.440 --> 02:21.171
- He's like a fish.
- Right.

02:21.240 --> 02:22.651
Well, keep fishing, eh?

02:42.640 --> 02:45.689
(SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

02:48.520 --> 02:49.681
MAN 1: Last bets, now.

02:49.760 --> 02:51.649
MAN 2: Now, don't go spending
all your rent money, Charlie.

02:53.080 --> 02:56.368
That's your starters, gentleman.
No more bets.

02:58.760 --> 03:00.205
- I was there on time.
- Finished.

03:00.840 --> 03:03.764
- I've had a tip off. I need this bet.
- The race has started...

03:03.840 --> 03:05.365
- Please.
-(SHOUTING) No!

03:05.440 --> 03:09.650
- Ugh. Fine.
- Get rid of him. I said no.

03:09.920 --> 03:13.242
- Now get out.
- All right, all right, I'm off. I'm off.

03:29.280 --> 03:31.965
- All right, lads. See you tomorrow.
- Cheers.

03:50.360 --> 03:51.486
(DOOR SHUTS)

03:52.600 --> 03:54.329
- It's a good day.
- Where's john?

03:54.720 --> 03:56.563
- John's in The Garrison.
-(SIGHS)

03:56.640 --> 03:58.722
Says he wants a meeting
about a family matter.

04:00.520 --> 04:03.808
After he's said his piece, he'll come
back and take his place with Scudboat.

04:04.560 --> 04:07.086
Scudboat, john will be
here in ten minutes.

04:07.160 --> 04:09.083
- All right.
- Five.

04:37.840 --> 04:39.205
We're here.

04:47.160 --> 04:48.321
Good boy.

04:58.960 --> 05:01.122
(COINS CLINKING)

05:06.480 --> 05:08.050
John?

05:17.240 --> 05:18.810
(ALL YELLING)

05:18.880 --> 05:19.881
Put that down!

05:22.120 --> 05:23.246
This is for Cheltenham.

05:24.320 --> 05:26.448
We just taking back what's ours.

05:27.120 --> 05:29.566
There's loot in here, search everywhere!

05:36.160 --> 05:39.642
All right, john. There's only one... Not
now. Only one man guarding the house.

05:40.960 --> 05:43.691
- What's troubling you?
-(CLEARS THROAT)

05:44.440 --> 05:48.206
Polly, you know what it's been like
since Martha died.

05:48.280 --> 05:50.248
God takes the best first.

05:50.320 --> 05:54.723
The truth is, my kids have been
running bloody rings around me.

05:55.640 --> 05:58.644
Running barefoot with the
dogs until all hours.

06:00.400 --> 06:02.607
Pol, give him ten bob for
some new shoes. Is that it, john?

06:02.680 --> 06:04.648
Tommy, we'd be better
to do this without you.

06:07.440 --> 06:08.601
Now, what's your point?

06:10.640 --> 06:13.120
What the kids need is a mother.

06:16.320 --> 06:17.890
So that's why I'm getting married.

06:19.720 --> 06:22.405
POLLY: Does this poor girl know you're
gonna marry her or are you just gonna

06:22.760 --> 06:24.728
spring it on her all of the sudden?

06:25.200 --> 06:26.440
I've already proposed.

06:26.560 --> 06:27.971
And she said yes.

06:28.360 --> 06:31.842
I think there's a shell about
to land and go bang.

06:35.400 --> 06:38.131
It's, um, it's Lizzie Stark.

06:38.200 --> 06:40.168
(CHUCKLING)

06:42.680 --> 06:45.206
john! Lizzie Stark's a strong woman,

06:45.320 --> 06:47.891
and I'm sure she provides
a fine service for her customers.

06:48.000 --> 06:49.923
I won't hear the word.

06:50.640 --> 06:53.086
Understand? Do not use that word.

06:53.600 --> 06:55.602
What word is that, john?

06:56.200 --> 06:59.522
- You know what word that is.
- Everybody bloody knows.

06:59.600 --> 07:01.170
Everybody can go to hell.

07:02.000 --> 07:05.322
Whore? That word.
Or prostitute? How about that one?

07:06.240 --> 07:11.280
All right, I want it known,
if anyone calls her a whore again,

07:11.360 --> 07:14.887
I will push the barrel of my
revolver down their throats,

07:14.960 --> 07:17.281
and blow the word back
down into their hearts.

07:17.360 --> 07:20.330
Men and their cocks never
cease to amaze me.

07:21.040 --> 07:24.123
John, Lizzie Stark never did
a day's work vertical.

07:24.200 --> 07:27.170
She's changed. All right, people change.

07:27.240 --> 07:29.527
Like with religion.

07:29.600 --> 07:31.807
Oh, Lizzie Stark's got religion, eh?

07:32.560 --> 07:34.483
No, no, she doesn't
have religion, but...

07:35.680 --> 07:37.125
Well, she loves me.

07:38.080 --> 07:42.051
Now, listen, Tommy. I won't do it
without your blessing.

07:43.800 --> 07:49.364
But of all the people in the world,
I want you to see it...

07:50.880 --> 07:53.406
- As brave.
- Oh, it's brave, all right.

07:53.480 --> 07:56.404
POLLY: Brave is going where no
man has gone before.

07:57.520 --> 08:00.603
And with Lizzie Stark, john, that is
really not what you'll be doing.

08:00.680 --> 08:01.727
Give me some time.

08:01.840 --> 08:03.365
Welcome her to the family

08:04.120 --> 08:06.282
as someone who's had a hard life.

08:07.760 --> 08:10.001
All right, because I need someone.

08:11.800 --> 08:13.450
All right, the kids need someone.

08:13.920 --> 08:16.844
(DOOR OPENS)
Tommy, we've been done over.

08:17.120 --> 08:18.167
What?

08:23.680 --> 08:25.205
Jesus Christ!

08:25.560 --> 08:27.324
What the bloody hell happened here?

08:27.920 --> 08:32.403
The Lees, all of them. Cousins, nephews.

08:32.799 --> 08:34.289
Even the bastards.

08:34.880 --> 08:37.042
POLLY: They've taken anything
they can lay their hands on.

08:39.840 --> 08:41.205
Four cash boxes.

08:43.159 --> 08:45.447
- They left these.
- Wire cutters?

08:46.040 --> 08:48.441
- Why would they leave wire cutters?
- Nobody move.

08:51.200 --> 08:52.929
I think our friends
are playing the game.

08:53.440 --> 08:57.411
- What game?
- Pol, don't, don't touch anything.

08:59.360 --> 09:01.010
Erasmus Lee was in France.

09:02.080 --> 09:03.206
Shit.

09:07.920 --> 09:10.161
When we gave up ground to the Germans,

09:11.520 --> 09:14.922
we'd leave behind booby traps
set up with wires.

09:16.160 --> 09:17.685
Then we'd leave wire cutters.

09:18.360 --> 09:19.407
It's part of the joke.

09:20.720 --> 09:22.688
Somewhere in here
there's a hand grenade.

09:22.840 --> 09:24.171
Holy Jesus.

09:26.040 --> 09:27.963
Attached to a wire.

09:29.920 --> 09:31.524
Don't move any chairs.

09:32.560 --> 09:34.369
Or open any doors.

09:37.720 --> 09:39.802
Go easy, john boy, easy.

09:40.080 --> 09:41.081
Ah!

09:41.440 --> 09:43.647
Boys, no, there's nothing here.

09:45.480 --> 09:47.642
If it was in here, it would
have blown by now.

09:48.400 --> 09:51.882
It was my name on
that bullet Erasmus sent.

09:52.960 --> 09:54.689
He set up a trap all right.

09:57.880 --> 09:59.291
He set it upjust for me.

10:13.200 --> 10:14.406
Finn?

10:15.880 --> 10:17.803
Finn, stay exactly where you are.

10:18.960 --> 10:21.088
(GIGGLES) I was pretending I was you.

10:23.880 --> 10:25.962
Which door did you
open to come in, Finn?

10:26.040 --> 10:28.008
I didn't, I climbed in.

10:29.880 --> 10:34.488
I want you to climb out exactly the
same way you climbed in, okay?

10:35.880 --> 10:37.689
- No, no, Finn!
- (CLATTERING)

10:39.600 --> 10:41.568
- Grenade!
-(ALL YELLING)

10:45.600 --> 10:47.250
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

11:03.800 --> 11:06.770
That's why you should
never pretend to be me.

11:07.440 --> 11:09.329
Okay? Okay?

11:29.720 --> 11:30.767
(WHISTLES)

11:46.280 --> 11:48.487
I got you ten minutes with her.

11:50.960 --> 11:53.930
You can at least say thank you.
It's easier to see the Pope, these days.

12:02.520 --> 12:03.601
(KNOCKING)

12:19.760 --> 12:20.966
(SIGHS)

12:26.000 --> 12:27.445
Put your hand on the Bible.

12:28.200 --> 12:29.201
I don't believe.

12:31.200 --> 12:32.884
Anyway, I didn't come here to lie.

12:34.520 --> 12:36.249
This war is cutting us all up.

12:37.520 --> 12:41.002
(SPEAKING ROMANIAN)

12:44.240 --> 12:47.164
- You're all children.
- I say enough.

12:47.960 --> 12:50.884
Your boys tried to kill me. Didn't work.

12:55.080 --> 12:57.970
(SPEAKING ROMANIAN)

13:06.280 --> 13:08.362
No wonder you won't touch a Bible.

13:08.760 --> 13:11.127
- I have ambitions.
- You want to play a switch.

13:12.320 --> 13:14.209
- I need your boys.
- For what?

13:14.520 --> 13:18.002
Kimber's not the brains,
there's a Gadza who runs the races.

13:18.880 --> 13:22.362
I'm collecting smart people,
but I need strong men, too.

13:23.000 --> 13:24.729
Now, your boys should know this.

13:25.920 --> 13:30.289
We now get the winner in one of three
races before the race even starts.

13:30.520 --> 13:33.603
No need for chalkers or rafflers,
I'm talking certainties.

13:33.680 --> 13:36.411
You come in here, boasting you're
gonna do someone down,

13:36.480 --> 13:38.482
and in the same breath,
ask me to trust you?

13:41.520 --> 13:44.285
On my mother's side, we are kin.

13:46.840 --> 13:50.208
(SPEAKING ROMANIAN)

13:59.640 --> 14:01.324
Ada, can you do my back?

14:04.480 --> 14:05.641
Ada!

14:07.360 --> 14:09.203
I know what was in the envelope.

14:10.560 --> 14:12.403
I looked. Money.

14:12.840 --> 14:16.322
And that bloke that we met in London,
who you said was a Frenchman,

14:16.400 --> 14:18.289
he was Russian.
I'm not an idiot, Freddie.

14:18.720 --> 14:21.200
How is it, that you take all the risks

14:21.280 --> 14:23.726
and Stanley Chapman gets the money?

14:23.920 --> 14:25.968
- It's money for the cause.
-(SCOFFS)

14:26.440 --> 14:27.680
You're blind.

14:28.080 --> 14:30.162
I would be, if your brothers
had anything to do with it.

14:30.240 --> 14:33.961
This isn't about them,
this is about you. And me.

14:34.240 --> 14:36.447
And this.

14:39.400 --> 14:42.006
(SIGHS) You're a dreamer, Freddie.

14:43.160 --> 14:46.050
You give money away
while we rot in here.

14:47.600 --> 14:49.648
You talk about revolution.

14:50.720 --> 14:51.846
I need to know.

14:56.040 --> 14:58.168
Who are you loyal to, Freddie?

15:01.360 --> 15:03.249
I said, who are you loyal to?

15:03.720 --> 15:04.846
(SIGHS)

15:22.840 --> 15:23.966
(DOOR OPENS)

15:31.880 --> 15:33.450
(DOOR LOCKS)

15:42.720 --> 15:44.529
Did you have something to do with this?

15:46.360 --> 15:48.249
I asked an acquaintance for an address.

15:48.960 --> 15:51.088
She said she'd only give
it to me anonymously.

15:51.760 --> 15:53.364
She's afraid of the consequences.

15:55.360 --> 15:56.521
Whose address is it?

15:57.720 --> 15:59.882
Tommy, I'd like to suggest a strategy.

16:20.880 --> 16:24.168
Your message said
you have an address for me?

16:28.960 --> 16:30.769
Anonymous tip off.

16:31.880 --> 16:34.087
The address of Stanley Chapman.

16:35.680 --> 16:39.366
- You promised me Freddie Thorne.
- This is instead of Freddie Thorne.

16:40.440 --> 16:42.283
- No deal.
- Inspector,

16:42.840 --> 16:45.844
Stanley Chapman is a bigger
fish than Freddie Thorne.

16:48.560 --> 16:51.211
He's currently holding £200 in cash

16:52.080 --> 16:55.562
given to The Communist Party
by the Russian government.

16:57.240 --> 17:00.722
That's right, Chapman
has snow on his boots.

17:01.120 --> 17:03.168
And all you need is a shovel.

17:04.000 --> 17:06.320
If he talks, you'll have proof.

17:07.880 --> 17:09.530
You might even get that medal.

17:11.200 --> 17:12.440
N ow,

17:13.760 --> 17:15.683
before I give you the address,

17:16.839 --> 17:18.171
I want your word

17:19.760 --> 17:21.444
that you'll let Freddie Thorne

17:21.880 --> 17:24.281
and my sister leave the city.

17:27.920 --> 17:30.127
Very well. You have my word.

17:35.760 --> 17:37.205
I'd say our little truce
has proven quite

17:37.280 --> 17:39.851
productive for both of us, Inspector.

17:41.640 --> 17:45.201
I'll get the information and protection.

17:46.160 --> 17:49.369
And you? Well...

17:50.960 --> 17:52.450
You get Bolsheviks.

17:57.320 --> 17:59.084
But on a more pressing matter,

18:01.680 --> 18:05.844
I'm afraid that Mr Churchill
is becoming impatient.

18:07.320 --> 18:08.810
And I fear that,

18:10.720 --> 18:13.564
if you don't get back
those stolen weapons soon,

18:14.480 --> 18:15.845
I will be replaced.

18:16.480 --> 18:18.482
That will be the finish
for me, that's for sure.

18:19.200 --> 18:21.487
When my business with Kimber is done,

18:21.800 --> 18:23.962
the guns will be returned.
That was the deal.

18:24.040 --> 18:26.646
Then I'm in your hands, completely.

18:28.560 --> 18:30.210
You hold all the cards.

18:31.560 --> 18:35.451
But, I hope to God that
my dismissal doesn't come

18:35.520 --> 18:38.763
before your decision to
hand back those guns.

18:39.400 --> 18:41.482
And I say this for your sake because,

18:43.080 --> 18:46.562
if I were to be fired,
and it were your fault,

18:49.080 --> 18:51.321
I would do things that
would shame the devil.

18:52.320 --> 18:53.367
<i>(caucus)</i>

18:53.920 --> 18:56.366
My fury is a thing to behold.

18:58.200 --> 19:00.680
On my last day in power, for example,

19:01.680 --> 19:02.966
I would see to it

19:04.040 --> 19:07.886
that you and your scum brothers have
your heads stoved in with mallets

19:08.160 --> 19:09.321
and spades.

19:11.520 --> 19:13.010
And your sister, too.

19:14.200 --> 19:17.409
That baby inside her would
be of no consequence to me.

19:18.440 --> 19:20.602
The only one to be spared

19:21.640 --> 19:23.608
would be your little brother Finn.

19:24.360 --> 19:27.842
He would, however, be lifted,
as a juvenile,

19:28.760 --> 19:31.570
and dumped in that part
of the adult prison

19:32.680 --> 19:36.571
where men have the most
appetite for boys like him.

19:38.200 --> 19:41.647
Oh, that would be
a dark day indeed, Mr Shelby,

19:43.000 --> 19:46.163
if my dismissal comes
before your decision.

19:47.360 --> 19:48.521
You understand?

19:51.040 --> 19:52.530
And know this,

19:55.000 --> 19:56.684
the clock is ticking.

20:26.280 --> 20:27.361
(SNIFF5)

20:29.800 --> 20:31.325
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

20:43.000 --> 20:44.604
(GRUNTING)

20:45.520 --> 20:47.329
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

20:51.560 --> 20:55.042
(MORE SHOUTING)

20:57.480 --> 20:58.845
(YELLING IN PAIN)

21:03.880 --> 21:05.530
Look what we found.

21:07.160 --> 21:09.925
Seems Stanley Chapman really
does have snow on his boots.

21:12.920 --> 21:15.605
Come on. Here we go.

21:19.640 --> 21:21.130
Mr Chapman...

21:22.760 --> 21:24.250
You're fucked.

21:35.320 --> 21:36.321
(DOOR OPENS)

21:38.840 --> 21:42.367
He still refuses to say
where it came from.

21:44.520 --> 21:46.443
I'm sure with a little persuasion

21:47.240 --> 21:48.890
he'll tell us everything he knows.

21:50.080 --> 21:53.129
Including the whereabouts
of Freddie Thorne.

21:54.000 --> 21:56.651
- Sir?
- Your face is a picture.

21:57.440 --> 21:58.885
But I thought you'd done a deal.

21:59.680 --> 22:02.490
- Oh, is that what you thought?
- Well, you gave your word.

22:04.080 --> 22:05.969
My word.

22:08.720 --> 22:12.202
People still talk about such
things in this idiotic century.

22:12.440 --> 22:15.011
My word to who?

22:16.160 --> 22:17.730
To a Peaky Blinder?

22:19.440 --> 22:23.240
Now, go on and interrogate
Mr Chapman until he tells

22:23.320 --> 22:26.130
us where we can find
Freddie Thorne and his wife.

22:27.400 --> 22:29.767
The source of the money
is of secondary importance.

22:32.680 --> 22:35.843
You think my campaign against
Shelby has become personal?

22:37.160 --> 22:38.161
Correct.

22:38.760 --> 22:41.445
Spot on, as they say in London society.

22:42.680 --> 22:45.843
Now, go and interrogate Mr Chapman.

22:47.160 --> 22:49.686
And do not make the mistake
of being too gentle.

22:51.480 --> 22:52.686
Right, sir.

23:24.760 --> 23:25.921
Today's her birthday.

23:28.960 --> 23:30.200
I know you never miss it.

23:31.280 --> 23:32.964
Then I'm lucky you're not a copper.

23:33.920 --> 23:36.161
- What do you want?
- Came to warn you.

23:38.360 --> 23:39.725
They've lifted Stanley Chapman.

23:40.760 --> 23:43.525
How do you know?
Police don't spill that information.

23:43.800 --> 23:45.643
I know because it was me and Tommy
who tipped him off.

23:46.440 --> 23:48.647
Tommy did a deal.
In return for safe passage

23:48.800 --> 23:50.802
for you and Ada,
he's given them Stanley and the money.

23:51.760 --> 23:53.000
Money? What money?

23:56.920 --> 23:59.048
- Who told you about the money?
- Who do you think?

24:01.360 --> 24:02.885
Yeah, it was Ada's idea.

24:03.560 --> 24:06.370
That's how desperate she is to get out
of that rat hole you're keeping her in.

24:09.720 --> 24:12.371
She didn't mind if you knew, just didn't
want to be here when you found out.

24:13.120 --> 24:15.964
Sometimes women have to take over.
Like in the war.

24:16.040 --> 24:17.849
Who the hell do you think you are?
You fucking Shelbys!

24:17.920 --> 24:19.570
Don't you swear over
your mother's grave.

24:22.640 --> 24:25.086
You play your tune, you expect
the whole world to dance to it.

24:25.160 --> 24:26.730
You don't have time for this, Freddie.

24:28.200 --> 24:29.725
You did a dealfor me.

24:30.160 --> 24:32.481
Don't flatter yourself. For Ada.

24:32.560 --> 24:34.403
And you think this copper
will keep his word?

24:35.600 --> 24:38.570
If he does, you're safe.
If he doesn't, Chapman will give you up.

24:38.840 --> 24:40.729
You'll still have to leave
town, same result.

24:42.680 --> 24:44.409
- So neat.
- So leave.

24:44.760 --> 24:46.489
Except there's one thing that
you've got wrong,

24:47.320 --> 24:50.449
Stanley won't be able to give up my
address because he doesn't know it.

24:51.360 --> 24:54.842
That's how it works.
None of us know each other's addresses.

24:56.120 --> 24:58.361
So you've wasted your fucking time.

24:59.920 --> 25:03.606
And they'll keep beating him and beating
him for information he doesn't have.

25:03.880 --> 25:07.362
So all you've done is sign the
death warrant of a good man.

25:09.560 --> 25:12.450
- So you won't leave?
- No, I won't fucking leave.

25:13.160 --> 25:16.767
And if you want me out of Birmingham,
it'll have to be in a wooden box.

25:22.360 --> 25:25.330
You lay a hand on our Ada and I'll
put you in a wooden box myself.

25:36.360 --> 25:38.806
You raised a stubborn one there, Irene.

26:06.560 --> 26:08.324
You told me to carry on.

26:08.400 --> 26:10.004
I wanted to stop.

26:10.600 --> 26:12.648
He had some kind of seizure.

26:16.840 --> 26:19.002
(SIGHS) So you killed him.

26:21.480 --> 26:22.641
Did he give you an address?

26:24.000 --> 26:26.731
What's the matter with you?
He fell down some stairs.

26:26.800 --> 26:28.928
This is not bloody Belfast.

26:29.120 --> 26:32.602
Not yet, but if men like him
get their way, it soon will be.

26:32.800 --> 26:37.408
So find some stairs, throw him
down, and call the coroner.

26:39.240 --> 26:40.366
Use Grayson.

26:41.360 --> 26:43.010
If he has any awkward questions,

26:43.160 --> 26:45.970
ask about the welfare of his mistress
in Saltley.

26:47.040 --> 26:48.610
That'll shut him up.

26:54.320 --> 26:56.800
To think I used to live
in a shithole like this.

26:57.400 --> 26:58.845
Bloody animals.

26:58.920 --> 27:01.730
The Shelbys really are doing
an excellentjob for us.

27:03.280 --> 27:04.566
We haven't lost a single penny to

27:04.640 --> 27:06.881
rafflers or chalkers
in eight race meetings.

27:07.480 --> 27:08.686
The bookies are purring.

27:08.920 --> 27:10.968
So we throw the dog a bone.

27:12.200 --> 27:13.201
I think so.

27:19.600 --> 27:23.082
Mr Kimber, Mr Roberts,
come and have a look around.

27:30.920 --> 27:32.001
After you.

27:32.120 --> 27:35.488
(IN DISTINCT CHATTER)

27:41.240 --> 27:43.163
Well, I thought the Lees
turned you over?

27:43.240 --> 27:45.641
You shouldn't listen to gossip,
Mr Kimber. This way.

27:48.760 --> 27:50.046
Business is good.

27:51.280 --> 27:52.850
Especially since now you know

27:52.920 --> 27:55.127
which horse is going to win
before you set the odds.

27:55.560 --> 27:57.961
Information is very much appreciated.

28:00.320 --> 28:02.243
All right, well, where are they?

28:03.200 --> 28:05.771
John, Lovelock. Scudboat, in here.

28:11.000 --> 28:12.331
This is my team.

28:13.000 --> 28:15.526
They will take up their pitch at your
convenience, Mr Kimber.

28:16.840 --> 28:20.049
John is the book, Scudboat is the
bag man, and of course,

28:20.280 --> 28:21.930
we bring our own protection.

28:24.440 --> 28:29.128
Warwick, next Saturday,
at least 50 yards from the beer tent.

28:55.560 --> 28:59.042
Gentleman, and lady.

29:00.880 --> 29:02.484
I have in my hand

29:02.880 --> 29:07.044
a legal betting license,
issued by the Board of Control.

29:08.600 --> 29:12.969
The Shelby family has its first, legal

29:13.480 --> 29:14.720
racetrack pitch.

29:14.880 --> 29:16.803
(ALL CHEERING)

29:24.640 --> 29:25.721
Congratulations.

29:26.080 --> 29:27.161
There you go.

29:28.680 --> 29:29.841
Congratulations.

29:30.480 --> 29:33.165
30, 40, 50...

29:40.680 --> 29:42.728
These cigarettes
have a strange smell, Arthur.

29:43.480 --> 29:45.881
They smell like rotting water.

29:46.160 --> 29:47.207
And look,

29:47.280 --> 29:48.725
rats have got into some of them.

29:50.400 --> 29:51.447
They're stolen, are they not?

29:51.560 --> 29:52.641
Don't ask.

29:53.560 --> 29:55.085
They smell because you
keep them in the boat.

29:55.160 --> 29:58.607
What do you care? Now, can you
come check my adding up, please?

30:04.200 --> 30:06.487
You know, you should make a
new start of this place.

30:06.960 --> 30:08.041
Do it propeflY-

30:08.440 --> 30:10.169
These cigarettes are not fit to sell.

30:10.760 --> 30:11.921
Smells like Gallipoli.

30:12.040 --> 30:14.327
You should find a new
place to store them.

30:14.440 --> 30:16.681
It has to be far away from coppers.

30:16.840 --> 30:18.171
Oh, but not rats.

30:18.280 --> 30:20.487
All the wharves have rats, Grace.

30:22.320 --> 30:23.924
What's wrong with a dry warehouse?

30:24.200 --> 30:25.326
Tommy's orders.

30:27.440 --> 30:28.566
What orders?

30:28.960 --> 30:32.282
Always keep contraband near
petrol boat moorings.

30:32.880 --> 30:34.211
Don't boats get searched?

30:34.280 --> 30:35.884
We moor them at junctions.

30:37.280 --> 30:38.850
So there's more than one way out.

30:39.240 --> 30:42.050
No locks within a mile
so we can move that stuff,

30:42.520 --> 30:43.601
fast.

30:44.200 --> 30:45.929
Your brother doesn't obey the law,
but he has rules.

30:46.480 --> 30:48.050
Precise man, your brother.

30:49.160 --> 30:50.366
I5 m)! adding up right?

30:50.480 --> 30:51.606
It is now.

30:54.240 --> 30:55.321
CAMPBELL: One.

30:55.720 --> 30:56.801
Two.

30:57.040 --> 30:58.087
Three.

30:58.560 --> 31:00.085
<i>And four.</i>

31:00.520 --> 31:02.807
<i>And we'll search them one-by-one.</i>

31:09.240 --> 31:13.450
Please, Lord, let that which
I seek be found here.

31:29.120 --> 31:31.248
Not so much as a bullet, sir.

31:31.360 --> 31:33.203
Just more cigarettes and whisky.

31:43.560 --> 31:45.562
Arthur tells me you've
been asking questions.

31:47.520 --> 31:49.010
About how we run our business

31:50.080 --> 31:51.411
and how we get our booze

31:51.720 --> 31:52.721
and where we keep it.

31:53.000 --> 31:54.286
I'm just trying to help.

31:57.440 --> 31:58.805
Let's you and me go for a walk.

32:00.360 --> 32:01.486
Where to?

32:01.560 --> 32:02.721
Come on.

32:12.200 --> 32:13.326
Why here?

32:16.000 --> 32:18.002
You're a good Catholic girl, aren't you?

32:20.280 --> 32:21.281
Yes.

32:21.760 --> 32:24.240
Well, then you know it's here
people come to confess.

32:25.560 --> 32:27.164
(SIGHS) After you.

32:38.800 --> 32:40.165
Well, here it is, Grace.

32:42.280 --> 32:43.406
I'll confess.

32:45.640 --> 32:46.721
I need someone.

32:49.160 --> 32:51.766
Kimber has an adviser by
the name of Roberts.

32:51.960 --> 32:53.246
He talks well.

32:53.640 --> 32:55.130
Keeps the accounts.

32:55.760 --> 32:57.649
Runs the legal side of the business.

32:58.960 --> 33:00.086
And you need a Roberts?

33:01.680 --> 33:03.170
Arthur tells me you have ideas.

33:03.960 --> 33:05.564
I'm not an accountant, nor a lawyer.

33:05.640 --> 33:06.721
No.

33:07.760 --> 33:09.489
No, but you have something I need.

33:10.880 --> 33:11.961
Class.

33:14.080 --> 33:16.447
I need someone who looks
right at the big meetings.

33:16.920 --> 33:18.365
Epsom, Ascot.

33:18.440 --> 33:19.771
Is this a job interview?

33:19.840 --> 33:21.330
Arthur says you're good with numbers.

33:21.400 --> 33:24.404
(LAUGHS) Oh, well, that's relative.
He's quite poor.

33:24.480 --> 33:25.481
(SCOFFS)

33:25.800 --> 33:27.245
You keep the books in order.

33:27.320 --> 33:28.560
They were chaotic.

33:29.560 --> 33:30.891
But you're a liar.

33:36.800 --> 33:38.564
No Catholic girl would enter a church

33:38.640 --> 33:40.404
and forget to make
the sign of the cross.

33:42.960 --> 33:44.007
You're very perceptive.

33:44.080 --> 33:46.924
First, you lied to me about that
pub you used to work in.

33:47.640 --> 33:49.563
Now I find out you're a Protestant.

33:52.640 --> 33:54.404
- Do you care?
- No.

33:55.320 --> 33:56.731
I like to fit in.

33:58.120 --> 33:59.326
You pull a pint

33:59.640 --> 34:01.085
like someone who's thinking about it.

34:01.200 --> 34:03.089
This is not an interview,
this is an interrogation.

34:03.160 --> 34:04.161
Sit down.

34:10.800 --> 34:11.926
Look, Grace.

34:12.760 --> 34:13.806
(SIGHS)

34:13.880 --> 34:15.609
You've washed up in a
place you don't belong,

34:16.440 --> 34:17.440
for whatever reason.

34:19.120 --> 34:20.360
My good fortune.

34:20.480 --> 34:21.719
And perhaps mine.

34:28.120 --> 34:29.929
You know that most of
what I do is illegal?

34:30.719 --> 34:31.846
I'm not blind.

34:32.560 --> 34:34.449
And yet you'd still be
willing to work for me?

34:37.400 --> 34:38.969
Are you offering me the job?

34:39.760 --> 34:40.761
(SCOFFS)

34:43.560 --> 34:44.561
Then I accept.

34:46.560 --> 34:47.925
There's something else you should know.

34:50.159 --> 34:53.083
A very important detail about
my reasons for employing you.

35:14.120 --> 35:15.406
You disappoint me.

35:19.120 --> 35:20.360
[)0 you resign?

35:22.920 --> 35:23.921
No.

35:25.080 --> 35:27.208
My appetite for the work
has only increased.

35:32.200 --> 35:33.201
(CLEARS TH ROAT)

35:34.160 --> 35:35.286
Tomorrow I'll show you around.

35:48.640 --> 35:49.766
Lizzie!

35:50.720 --> 35:52.210
Hello, Lizzie?

35:53.480 --> 35:55.608
That bag looks heavy. jump in!

35:55.760 --> 35:57.091
It is.

35:57.240 --> 35:58.446
You like kids?

35:59.040 --> 36:00.610
- Yeah.
- Good,

36:00.720 --> 36:02.085
because John's got four of them.

36:03.920 --> 36:06.491
It's all right, I'm not going
to try to talk you out of it.

36:23.640 --> 36:24.766
I just want to talk.

36:25.680 --> 36:26.681
Then you're against us?

36:27.680 --> 36:29.170
John is his own man.

36:30.400 --> 36:31.526
And you're your own woman.

36:35.960 --> 36:36.961
Now, Lizzie,

36:37.920 --> 36:41.242
since I came back from France,
I've come to you on many occasions.

36:43.080 --> 36:44.605
Tommy, you didn't tell him?

36:45.080 --> 36:46.366
No, I didn't tell him.

36:47.520 --> 36:49.204
Just like you didn't tell him.

36:50.680 --> 36:52.045
Now, why didn't you tell him, Lizzie?

36:53.200 --> 36:54.531
Why didn't you tell him

36:55.120 --> 36:57.930
that you've been serving
his brother for the past two years?

36:59.640 --> 37:01.005
Because the past is the past.

37:03.120 --> 37:04.929
I don't want to lose him.
He's a good man.

37:06.520 --> 37:09.683
That was the answer I was hoping
you'd give. The past is the past.

37:10.200 --> 37:12.123
You see, ourjohn says you've changed.

37:12.280 --> 37:14.647
And I believe him, and that's good.

37:15.200 --> 37:16.361
Change is good.

37:18.480 --> 37:20.209
These are new times I'm told.

37:24.200 --> 37:26.043
So I wish you both every happiness.

37:27.400 --> 37:31.962
And I want you to see that as
my wedding gift to you

37:33.480 --> 37:34.811
and our farewell

37:34.880 --> 37:36.086
to pleasures gone by.

37:49.240 --> 37:50.241
You mean...

37:51.480 --> 37:52.641
One last time?

37:55.000 --> 37:56.081
One last time.

37:56.480 --> 37:57.481
You and me.

38:00.560 --> 38:01.686
It's eight bloody pounds.

38:04.400 --> 38:05.401
(SCOFFS)

38:22.200 --> 38:23.201
So where should we go?

38:26.840 --> 38:28.365
Tommy, should we go to my lodging?

38:32.280 --> 38:34.123
So the past is not the past.

38:37.360 --> 38:39.203
You can keep the money, Lizzie,
just get out of the car.

38:39.280 --> 38:41.044
- Tommy, please!
-just get out of the car.

38:41.440 --> 38:43.124
I love him, Tommy, really.

38:45.280 --> 38:46.281
Really.

38:54.240 --> 38:55.685
John will make his own decision.

38:57.520 --> 38:58.681
But he will have the facts.

39:01.760 --> 39:04.001
Your brother is ten times
the man you are.

39:14.560 --> 39:15.971
(SIGHS)

39:16.320 --> 39:18.084
Of that I have no doubt.

39:37.600 --> 39:39.284
Well, he's obviously not stupid.

39:40.120 --> 39:42.407
All we found was stolen
tobacco and whisky.

39:42.760 --> 39:43.966
Which you left it in place?

39:44.320 --> 39:45.401
Of course.

39:45.880 --> 39:47.325
I would never endanger you.

39:52.880 --> 39:54.041
You're doing well, Grace.

39:56.120 --> 39:57.929
I've been working on Arthur.
He's easier.

39:58.720 --> 39:59.721
Than Thomas?

39:59.840 --> 40:00.841
Yes.

40:01.520 --> 40:02.760
Less intelligent.

40:03.880 --> 40:04.881
Yes.

40:05.480 --> 40:07.642
That's not a word you'd
use about Thomas.

40:07.840 --> 40:08.841
It's your word.

40:11.600 --> 40:12.601
He has promoted me.

40:13.880 --> 40:16.531
He wants me to be
his bookkeeper and secretary.

40:18.800 --> 40:21.121
A cut-throat gangster with a secretary.

40:22.160 --> 40:25.323
The pretensions of these
hoodlums are quite breathtaking.

40:26.080 --> 40:27.081
Are they not?

40:27.720 --> 40:29.324
Yes, quite breathtaking.

40:32.640 --> 40:35.689
He's obviously fallen
quite heavily for you.

40:36.360 --> 40:37.521
I thought you'd be pleased.

40:39.160 --> 40:41.049
I just hope you remember who
you're dealing with, here.

40:41.160 --> 40:44.164
A man who cuts off ears
and cuts out tongues.

40:45.120 --> 40:46.531
I know what he is, sir.

40:48.760 --> 40:54.005
The difficulty with undercover work,
Grace, is to remember what you are.

40:55.520 --> 40:57.648
I come here with
good news and I get this?

41:01.680 --> 41:02.727
Grace.

41:20.640 --> 41:21.687
Tommy.

41:22.280 --> 41:23.486
I need a favour.

41:23.800 --> 41:25.006
I want to borrow the car.

41:25.560 --> 41:27.847
I want to take Lizzie for a ride
in the country with the kids.

41:28.640 --> 41:30.210
I'm going to celebrate
getting the license.

41:30.720 --> 41:32.006
Not a problem,john.

41:33.880 --> 41:34.881
I need the keys.

41:37.400 --> 41:38.731
Look, john, you're my brother.

41:41.480 --> 41:42.641
There's something I have to tell you.

41:45.120 --> 41:47.771
Yesterday, in the front
seat of that ca r,

41:48.600 --> 41:50.204
I offered Lizzie some money.

41:51.920 --> 41:52.921
And, john,

41:53.680 --> 41:55.045
she said yes.

41:57.120 --> 41:58.485
Now that's a fact.

41:58.800 --> 42:00.245
You do with it what you want.

42:01.360 --> 42:02.566
You can take the keys,

42:03.080 --> 42:07.005
take Lizzie to the country.
Marry her, if you want.

42:08.800 --> 42:09.961
But you have to know...

42:11.640 --> 42:12.880
She said yes.

42:21.000 --> 42:22.001
(SIGHS)

42:41.840 --> 42:42.841
(EXHALES)

42:56.480 --> 42:57.481
Get another glass.

42:58.120 --> 42:59.121
(CLEARS TH ROAT)

43:08.120 --> 43:09.121
Can you make a toast?

43:10.440 --> 43:12.807
I'm Irish, I can make a million toasts.

43:13.560 --> 43:17.281
May you be in Heaven a full half-hour
before the devil knows you're dead.

43:24.480 --> 43:25.527
What are we celebrating?

43:25.920 --> 43:28.446
Contract of employment.

43:28.880 --> 43:30.006
(CLEARS TH ROAT)

43:30.360 --> 43:32.840
"Bookkeeper, Shelby Brothers Limited."

43:33.200 --> 43:35.168
I don't like that word, "Limited".

43:36.120 --> 43:37.770
To be respectable,
you have to be limited.

43:37.840 --> 43:39.524
That's what worries me.

43:41.560 --> 43:42.891
I had the phone put in.

43:45.080 --> 43:46.081
It's in the back.

43:48.520 --> 43:50.488
Huh. If I knew someone
else who had a phone,

43:51.160 --> 43:52.286
we could call them.

43:54.200 --> 43:55.770
And since we're celebrating,

43:57.360 --> 44:00.204
I had this delivered from
Rackhams department store.

44:04.480 --> 44:05.561
Will you open it?

44:07.080 --> 44:08.206
No.

44:08.600 --> 44:10.648
Save it for a special occasion.

44:12.720 --> 44:14.449
<i>PM fight, your first 'yob
for the company.</i>

44:15.200 --> 44:16.645
I want you to get that to my sister.

44:17.640 --> 44:18.641
You don't see her?

44:18.880 --> 44:21.281
No one does. She's hiding from me.

44:23.800 --> 44:26.770
I was told she goes to a bathhouse
on Montague Street

44:27.280 --> 44:28.645
on women-only days.

44:29.240 --> 44:31.481
She goes in disguise so
I need to get someone inside.

44:32.440 --> 44:33.441
What am I delivering?

44:36.320 --> 44:37.685
It's an invitation

44:38.120 --> 44:40.282
to a family occasion. I want her there.

44:41.000 --> 44:42.365
Tell her there'll be a truce.

44:42.600 --> 44:44.409
Am I delivering bait for a trap?

44:45.560 --> 44:47.005
If you take that contract,

44:47.680 --> 44:50.001
I think you'll find it doesn't say
anything about asking questions.

44:50.480 --> 44:51.811
Just give her the invitation.

44:53.840 --> 44:55.888
And put that thing in the
cupboard till I say.

45:08.760 --> 45:10.171
(FOOTSTEPS IN DISTANCE)

45:37.920 --> 45:39.331
(SIGHS) Bloody hell, john.

45:39.440 --> 45:41.488
I couldn't get it lit.
Couldn't even do that.

45:42.280 --> 45:43.805
What do you want to be smoking that for?

45:43.960 --> 45:45.485
Same FGHSOH HS YOU.

45:46.000 --> 45:47.240
Pain in the head.

45:57.960 --> 45:59.849
I spoke to Lizzie.

46:00.520 --> 46:02.010
Told her what you told me.

46:04.360 --> 46:06.647
She said, "Your brother Tommy
is a dirty liar."

46:08.480 --> 46:10.960
And then I spoke to her
sister and her cousin.

46:11.400 --> 46:12.925
I bought them a couple of drinks.

46:14.320 --> 46:16.209
Just a few regulars, they said.

46:17.160 --> 46:18.366
That's all.

46:19.960 --> 46:22.440
To keep the wolf from
the door she still sees

46:22.640 --> 46:24.165
a couple of regulars.

46:26.080 --> 46:27.764
(SNIFFLES) You must think I'm an idiot!

46:37.920 --> 46:40.321
I think you're the first
Shelby in history

46:41.200 --> 46:43.043
to have a legal license for anything.

46:43.160 --> 46:44.161
<i>(SRO ANS)</i>

46:46.120 --> 46:47.929
What would our granddad say, eh?

46:49.120 --> 46:50.929
He'd be turning in his grave.

46:51.920 --> 46:53.524
"Honest bloody money!

46:53.920 --> 46:57.242
"Hey, in this house? Here?"

46:57.320 --> 46:59.561
You always used to do voices
when we were kids.

47:03.760 --> 47:05.683
Well, we're not kids now, john.

47:08.400 --> 47:10.482
But we still have to look
out for each other, right?

47:13.680 --> 47:14.681
Yeah.

47:16.200 --> 47:17.201
Yeah.

47:18.120 --> 47:19.610
Come on, go home.

47:20.880 --> 47:21.881
Get some sleep.

47:23.320 --> 47:24.810
We've got a big day tomorrow.

47:25.800 --> 47:26.801
We have?

47:28.280 --> 47:31.409
Tomorrow, we finish the war
with the Lees for once and for all.

47:33.400 --> 47:35.721
- Since when?
- Since just now.

47:37.080 --> 47:38.081
Ten o'clock, tomorrow.

47:40.960 --> 47:42.325
Be ready for anything.

47:50.880 --> 47:51.881
How do you g0. bOYS?

